solutions.content:
Either pick all k from previous piles, or choose j from current pile and pick k-j from previous piles
**Recurrence relation**:
`f(n,k)` represents the max sum of coins collected from first `n` piles and choosing `k` top coins.
```
f(n,k) = max(
			f(n-1,k) // pick k from previous n-1 piles
			,max(f(n-1,k-j-1)+sum(0 to j) for j = 0 to min(k,p[n-1].size())) // pick j+1 from current pile and k-j-1 from previous n-1 piles
		)
```
if k = 0, i.e. you can't pick any coin then ans = 0
if n = 0, i.e. you don't have any piles then ans = 0
**Base cases** :
`f(0,k) = 0`
`f(n,0) = 0`

```
/*
f(i,k) = max(f(i-1,k),max(f(i-1,k-j-1)+sum(j) for j = 0 to max(k,p[i-1].length)))
f(i,0) = 0
f(0,k) = 0
*/
class Solution {
    public int maxValueOfCoins(List<List<Integer>> piles, int K) {
        int n = piles.size();
        int[][] dp = new int[n+1][K+1];

        for(int i = 1; i <= n; i ++) {
            for(int k = 1; k <= K; k ++) {
                dp[i][k] = dp[i-1][k];
                int sum = 0;
                int picked = 1;
                for(int v: piles.get(i-1)) {
                    if(k-picked < 0) {
                        break;
                    }
                    sum += v;
                    dp[i][k] = Math.max(dp[i][k], dp[i-1][k-picked]+sum);
                    picked ++;
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[n][K];
    }
}
```

