solutions.content:
In the problem, we have to select ****K**** coins from the given piles of coins. In one step we can select one coin from the top of the n piles.
Our task is to ****maximize the total money we can get****.
From the ith pile, we can select between 0 to k coins.
Therefore, for every pile we have choice to take 0 coin to k coins. Simply, we can write the recursive code exploring all the choices.

**Recursive Solution-**

```
class Solution {
public:
    int fun(vector<vector<int>>& piles,int ind,int k)
    {
        if(k==0 )return 0; // no more coins can be taken
        if(ind==piles.size())return INT_MIN;// no more piles are left
        int ans=fun(piles,ind+1,k); // if we take 0 coin from the pile
        int score=0;
        int secAns=INT_MIN;
        for(int i=0;i<k && i<piles[ind].size();i++)// taking 1 to k coins from the pile
        {
            score+=piles[ind][i];
            secAns=max(secAns,score+fun(piles,ind+1,k-i-1));
        }
        return max(ans,secAns);                                      
    }

    int maxValueOfCoins(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int k) {
        int n=piles.size();
        return fun(piles,0,k);
    }
};
```
As we can clearly see, we have overlapping subproblems, therefore,  we can solve the problem with the help of Dynamic Programming. 
The state variables for the given dynamic programming problem are ind(index) and k. 
We can create a **dp[n][k+1]** and store the answer for the problem with i and k state variables.

**Dynamic Programming (Memoization)-**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int fun(vector<vector<int>>& piles,int ind,int k,vector<vector<int>>&dp)
    {
        if(k==0 )return 0;   //no more coins can be taken 
        if(ind==piles.size())return INT_MIN; // no more piles are left
        if(dp[ind][k]!=-1)return dp[ind][k]; // if already calculated, simply return
        int ans=fun(piles,ind+1,k,dp); // if we take 0 coin from the pile
        int score=0;
        int secAns=INT_MIN;
        for(int i=0;i<k && i<piles[ind].size();i++) // taking 1 to k coins from the pile
        {
            score+=piles[ind][i];
            secAns=max(secAns,score+fun(piles,ind+1,k-i-1,dp));
        }
        return dp[ind][k] = max(ans,secAns);                                      
    }

    int maxValueOfCoins(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int k) {
        int n=piles.size();
        vector<vector<int>>dp(n,vector<int>(k+1,-1));
        return fun(piles,0,k,dp);
    }
};
```
The above is the memoized dynamic programming solution.

