# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Looking at the problem, it is very obvious that it is an extension of Knapsack problem. The similarity is that here we can from each pile choose at most min(k, size of the current pile) and at least no coins.
We move through all the piles one by one collecting zero or more coins from each of them. At the end when we pass the last index and reach the nth position, we make sure that we have taken exactly k coins.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach is very simple considering that you have solved 0/1 Knapsack problem.
1. We maintain an index i for the current pile.
2. Value K is maintained for the number of coins that are yet to be used.
3. In each pile we traverse j from 0 to pile[i].size() in order to add the current coin to currVal which is initialized zero.
4. When j == 0, we do not add anything as we can also choose to leave the complete pile and in all the other cases we add the piles[i][j - 1] to the currVal and then make a call for the next pile (i + 1);
5. At the end when we reach the nth index, we check that we have k == 0 and return 0 otherwise we return -1e9;
6. From each recursive call we return maxVal which is initialized to be -1e9 and is maximised with every recusrive call.

# Recusrive Solution (TLE)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int f(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int n, int i, int k) {
        if (i == n) {
            if (!k) return 0;
            return -1e9;
        }
        int maxVal = -1e9, currVal = 0;
        for (int j = 0; j <= piles[i].size(); j++){
            if (j == 0) maxVal = max(maxVal, f(piles, n, i + 1, k));
            else if (k - j >= 0){
                currVal += piles[i][j - 1];
                maxVal = max(maxVal, currVal + f(piles, n, i + 1, 
                k - j));
            }
        }
        return maxVal;
    }

    int maxValueOfCoins(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int k) {
        int n = piles.size();
        return f(piles, n, 0, k);
    }
};
```

# Memoization Solution

# Complexity
**Time complexity:**
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n * k * maximum pile size)$$

**Space complexity:**
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n * k) + Auxiliiary Stack Space$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int f(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int n, int i, int k, 
    vector<vector<int>>& dp) {
        if (i == n) {
            if (!k) return 0;
            return -1e9;
        }
        if (dp[i][k] != -1) return dp[i][k];
        int maxVal = -1e9, currVal = 0;
        for (int j = 0; j <= piles[i].size(); j++){
            if (j == 0) maxVal = max(maxVal, f(piles, n, i + 1, k, dp));
            else if (k - j >= 0){
                currVal += piles[i][j - 1];
                maxVal = max(maxVal, currVal + f(piles, n, i + 1, 
                k - j, dp));
            }
        }
        return dp[i][k] = maxVal;
    }

    int maxValueOfCoins(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int k) {
        int n = piles.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(k + 1, - 1));
        return f(piles, n, 0, k, dp);
    }
};
```

# Dynamic Programming Solution

# Complexity
Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n * k * maximum pile size)$$

Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n * k)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxValueOfCoins(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int k) {
        int n = piles.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n + 1, vector<int>(k + 1, -1e9));
        dp[n][0] = 0;

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            for (int K = 0; K <= k; K++) {
                int maxVal = -1e9, currVal = 0;
                for (int j = 0; j <= piles[i].size(); j++){
                    if (j == 0) 
                        maxVal = max(maxVal, dp[i + 1][K]);
                    else if (K - j >= 0){
                        currVal += piles[i][j - 1];
                        maxVal = max(maxVal, currVal + dp[i + 1][K - j]);
                    }
                }
                dp[i][K] = maxVal;
            }
        }
        return dp[0][k];
    }
};
```

# Space Optimized Dynamic Programming Solution

# Complexity
Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n * k * maximum pile size)$$

Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(k)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxValueOfCoins(vector<vector<int>>& piles, int k) {
        int n = piles.size();
        vector<int> prev(k + 1, -1e9), curr(k + 1, -1e9);
        prev[0] = 0;

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            for (int K = 0; K <= k; K++) {
                int maxVal = -1e9, currVal = 0;
                for (int j = 0; j <= piles[i].size(); j++){
                    if (j == 0) 
                        maxVal = max(maxVal, prev[K]);
                    else if (K - j >= 0){
                        currVal += piles[i][j - 1];
                        maxVal = max(maxVal, currVal + prev[K - j]);
                    }
                }
                curr[K] = maxVal;
            }
            prev = curr;
        }
        return prev[k];
    }
};
```

