Fix the a constant purchase of either item.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- By setting constant purchase calculate number of times it can be purchased without considering purchase of other item. 
- Then gradually decrease the number of items fixed item can be purchase until simultaneously increase purchase of other item by considering the amount left after purchasing fixed item.
- Decrease till number of fixed item can be purchased is 0.
# Complexity
- Time complexity: Depends upon the input of `cost1` or `cost2`
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: Constant
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public long waysToBuyPensPencils(int total, int cost1, int cost2) {
        long ways = 0;
        int np = total/cost1; // NUMBER OF TIMES PEN CAN BE PURCHASED
        for(int i=0; i<=np; i++){
            ways += (total-(cost1*i))/cost2+1; // DECREASE THE NUMBER OF TIMES PEN CAN BE PURCHASED AND INCREASE THE PURCHASE OF PENCILS
// + 1 IS THERE CAUSE WE CAN ALSO SELECT 0 PENCIL AS OPTION
// USE OPERATOR OVERLOADING INSTEAD OF EXTRA MEMORY FOR CONVERTING TO LONG
        }
        return ways;
    }
}
```

