solutions.content:
A perfect DP problem for a beginner to start with. How about we store states using memoization.

One thing worth noticing is that for every multiple of cost1 or cost2 our dp array gets filled using previous values.
Let's initialize first element with '1' as per explained in second sample case. Now, iterate over all the possibilities and populate our dp array accordingly, doing for both cost 1 and 2.

Finally, summing our dp array we got our number of ways.

```
using ll = long long;
class Solution {
public:
    ll waysToBuyPensPencils(int n, int c1, int c2) {
        vector<ll> dp(n+1,0);
        dp[0] = 1;
        for(int i=c1; i<=n; ++i) dp[i] += dp[i - c1];
        for(int i=c2; i<=n; ++i) dp[i] += dp[i - c2];
        return accumulate(dp.begin(), dp.end(), 0LL);
    }
};
```

Time complexity :- O(n - c1 + 1) + O(n - c2 + 1) + O(n+1) = O(n)
Space complexity :- O(n)

Although I believe, it can be solved much efficiently using combinatorics and greedy but a solution worth mentioning in interviews. 😉

