# Intuition
* Since it was a medium problem, I thought it would be difficult but came up with a solution pretty quickly.

# Approach
* We've used HashMap in our code to track the values that we've visited previously. Here's the walkthrough.
    * First we initialize a HashMap with <Integer, Integer> datatype.
    * Then we set the value min to Integer.MAX_VALUE ( which is 2147483647 ) because intitializing min with -1 tends to stay minimum always when comparing with any size of desired output.
    * We traverse through the array only once and check if the Map contains the key value already.
    * If true, we calculate the difference between the two occurences and compare it with previous min value to evaluate the least one amongst them.
    * Else we simply add it to the map along with its index. We also add duplicate elements to the Map since the difference between similar elements may vary later.
    * We check whether the min value is still Integer.MAX_VALUE. If true, we simply return -1 which means no minimum consecutive elements with a single pair is found.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
    * The time complexity of for loop is O(n). But for HashMap it is O(1). So the total time complexity is O(n).

- Space complexity:
    * The space complexity is O(n). 

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumCardPickup(int[] cards) {
        Map<Integer, Integer> hm=new HashMap<Integer,Integer>();
        int min=Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for(int i=0;i<cards.length;i++)
        {
            if(hm.containsKey(cards[i]))
            {
                min=Math.min(min,(i+1)-hm.get(cards[i]));
            }
            hm.put(cards[i],i);
        }
        if(min==Integer.MAX_VALUE)
            min=-1;
        return min;
    }
}
```

