# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Every optimal sol will have first and the last card to be same. And this will be our variant to select the size of the window.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

Using hashing in the elements of the window we are keeping track of the window elements and whenever we are encountering any new element (i.e right most element) that is already present int the hash map we are checking if  the left most element is also same or not. If not then we are just decreasing the window size till our condition is satisfied.
Now when decreasing the window we are also deleting the left elements from the hash map. And updating the ans accordingly.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumCardPickup(vector<int>& cards) {

        unordered_map<int,int> h_map;

        int left=0,right=0;
        int ans=INT_MAX;
        while(right<cards.size())
        {
            auto ptr= h_map.find(cards[right]);
            if(ptr==h_map.end())
                h_map.insert({cards[right],right});
            else
            {                
                while(cards[right]!=cards[left])
                {   
                    h_map.erase(cards[left]); 
                    left++;
                }
                ans=min(ans,right-left+1);
                //cout<<"left: "<<left<<" right: "<<right<<"  ans: "<<ans<<endl;
                ptr->second=right;
                left++;
            }
            right++;
        }
        if(ans==INT_MAX)
            return -1;
        return ans;
    }
};
```

